observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Management to:

hold the Bids and Awards Committee as well as the Technical Working Group to liable for the approval of the eligibility of BV Three Two Four Printing and Trading as a legally, technically, and financially capable supplier in the absence of valid ITR and OSS during evaluation of bids until post qualification;

instruct the BAC to require the winning supplier to the original copy of Omnibus Sworn Statement for evaluation cited under Sections 3.4 and 4.1 of the GPPB Circular No. 01-2020;

instruct the TWG to require the supplier to submit a copy of their approved application for DTI registration of business form for verification of their main line of business officially registered with the DTI; and

require the BAC and the TWG to observe the provision in the submission of required documents in the evaluation of the eligibility of the supplier and refrain from recommending the award in the absence of valid documents.

We recommended the Management to:

institute administrative sanction against BAC and TWG for failing to properly evaluate the eligibility requirements of the supplier as well as its proficiency in transacting food products and failing to ensure that the food products sold by the supplier complied with the FDA regulatory test before awarding of contract contrary to the prescribed regulations in Sections 3.4 to 4.3 GPPB Circular 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020;

issue a Blacklisting Order following the provisions under the Uniform Guidelines for Blacklisting of Manufacturers, Suppliers, Distributors, Contractors, and Consultants as authorized through Section 10 (a) of GPPB Circular 01-2020 to disqualify the supplier from participating in the bidding of all government projects for failing to faithfully perform its obligation by delivering unregistered products;

make representations with the Food and Drug Administration to communicate the sale of unregistered canned goods by the supplier for their appropriate action and investigation to pronounce the proper decision for the case subject to the penalties provided in Section 12 of RA No. 3720 as amended by Section 11 of RA No. 9711; 

refrain from procuring food products that did not pass through safety and quality test with the Food and Drug Administration in strict observance of Republic Act No. 9711 or the Food and Drug Administration Act of 2009;

require the Social Welfare Officer to submit the i) special order issued as basis for the additional provision of welfare goods to frontliners; ii) the  Relief Distribution Sheet for the said frontliners; iii) the duly acknowledged list of recipients of 17,831 food packs;  and for the MDRRM Officer to submit the original copies of the RDS from the remaining barangays for verification of the actual number of families who received the food packs; 
require the Municipal Inspectorate Committee and Acceptance Team namely; Luisito M. Navarro, Ria M. Lamac, Ronilo H. Loto, Dennis M. Jambalos and Ramonchito L. Larga, the Head of the Requesting Office, as well as the approving body to submit satisfactory explanation as to acceptance of the delivery of the unregistered canned goods and the subsequent distribution of such to communities and as to why they should not be held liable for accepting unregistered products; and
require the GSO and/or SPU to submit a justifiable explanation for failing to include the brand name of the canned goods in the Purchase Order and to observe COA Circular No. 96-010 in the future transactions by including the brand names of the products procured by them.

We recommended the Management to require the:

members of the BAC, its Technical Working Group and those who conducted the negotiations with the participating suppliers to provide the basis in the assessment of capability of these suppliers to supply goods/items required by the Municipality;

BAC to strictly adhere with the appropriate procedures prescribed under R.A. No. 9184 and the 2016 Implementing Rules and Regulations for a particular mode of procurement adopted by the Municipality and the approving officials to ensure that appropriate procurement mode was adopted each procurement activity;

require the winning supplier to submit the proof of authority by the alleged representative to participate in the instant procurement activity in his/her behalf; 

those who conducted the negotiation and evaluation of offers/quotations to submit a justifiable explanation why they should not be held liable for the noted irregularities specifically on bids submitted by other participating suppliers were prepared using the same format, same font and printed in one and the same printer; and

members of the BAC and its TWG to conduct matching of line of business as indicated in the documents submitted by the participating suppliers with the type, nature or categories of the goods/items to be purchased to ensure that the Municipality negotiates with those eligible and registered for the type of goods/items subject of the purchase.

For the above observation raised, we recommended the Management to:
require the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to (i) furnish the Municipal Accounting Office a list of unreleased/unclaimed of checks at year-end which will be the basis for the preparation of Journal Entry Voucher to restore to the Cash in Bank account the amount of cash from these unclaimed/unreleased checks and to recognize the appropriate liability/payable account at year-end; (ii) regularly notify the payees of checks which have remained unclaimed/unreleased;
require the Municipal Accountant to effect adjusting entries to restore the total amount of unclaimed/unreleased checks as of year-end in the Cash in Bank account and recognize appropriate liability account to reflect the correct balances of these accounts at year-end.

We reiterated our recommendations to the Management to:
require the registration of all real estate owned by the Municipality under the Torrens Title System pursuant to COA Circular No. 92-386;
upon completion of the land titling, require the Municipal Accountant to; i) prepare the necessary entries and record the cost incurred in the purchase or fair value if acquired through donation or transfers without cost of the land, and: ii) record the parcels of land in its books after obtaining certified copy of the documents used in the titling of the said lands and ensuring that these are not identified or the same with any of the lands recorded in the books.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Management instruct:
the Municipal Engineering Office to determining the actual status of the aforementioned projects which were reported as complete and issue the corresponding certificate of completion;
the Municipal Accountant (i) to effect necessary adjustment in the books for projects reported as complete in order to reflect the correct balances of the CIP accounts, (ii) prepare the adjusting entries for completed projects transferred to the related/appropriate PPE account and, (iii) to provide the corresponding depreciation for the aforementioned assets; (iv) conduct evaluation on recorded amounts in the CIP accounts for projects which were reported as suspended for as far as CY 2004.

We recommended the Management to require the Municipal Accountant to:
analyze and confirm outstanding payables aged two or more with no valid and actual claims filed, for possible reversion to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund pursuant to Section 98 of PD No. 1445;
ensure to reflect only in the books amounts of valid obligations of the Municipality and must contained complete details of actual claimants;
evaluate and effect the necessary correcting/adjustment entry to reclassify payables erroneously recognized as Accounts Payables and Other Payables to proper liability account;
refrain from recognizing accounts payable with incomplete supporting document.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations and the Management agreed to:

strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated   December 19, 2016 and COA Circular No. 2012-004 dated November 28, 2012 on the required analysis of dormant accounts by performing the regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of the existence of the receivables for strict monitoring and disposition of said accounts; and for possible request for the write off of the specified dormant receivables to the Commission on Audit; 

determine the amount of the receivables impaired and provide for allowance for impairment for dormant receivables in order to have a fair presentation of the financial statements as required under IPSAS 29. Compute/determine impairment in accordance with the International Public Sector Accounting Standards or Philippine Financial Reporting Standards;

comply with all the conditions and requirements of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 for the possible request for the write off of the specified dormant receivables accounts to the Commission on Audit.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation and the Management agreed to: 

require the Municipal Treasurer to strictly intensify existing measures and strategies in the collection of taxes and generate more income through conduct of more rigid tax campaign and continuously post Notice of Delinquency to publicly accessible and conspicuous place such as entrance of Municipal Building, Markets and the likes, for a wider dissemination of the notice;

continuously coordinate with the barangays in the implementation of collection programs to maximize collection of taxes;

likewise, avail of remedies and sanctions as provided in RA No. 7160 for the delayed and/or non-payment of taxes.

We recommended that the Management:

require the BAC and the TWG to submit justifiable explanation on recommending award of contract although the mandatory documentary requirements were only submitted after award, otherwise held them liable for non-compliance with the guidelines for emergency procurement;

consider reorganizing the composition of the BAC and its Technical Working Group and require them to attend trainings, seminars and reorientation of the procurement law including the updates thereto.

The Audit Team recommended that the Management:

require the Municipal Accountant to submit justification on the incomplete time in and out in the DTRs and inconsistencies noted in the DTRs attached in payroll of salaries and wages as compared to DTRs in the payment of hazard pay;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure the completeness of the supporting documents and propriety of the claims before processing the payments;

require the immediate submission of the approved AWA of the following offices to facilitate conduct of validation: Municipal Mayor’s Office, Municipal Vice Mayor’s Office, Sangguniang Bayan Legislative Office, Municipal Nutrition Office, Municipal Social Welfare and Development Office, Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office, Street Lighting Section, Parks, Plaza and Monuments Section, Roads and Bridges Section, Street Cleaning Section, Municipal Assessor’s Office, Municipal Budget Office, Municipal Accounting Office, Slaughterhouse, Municipal Agriculture Office, Municipal Health Office, Information and Communications Technology Section, and Municipal Peace and Order Council- Other General Services;

strictly observe compliance with Budget Circular No. 2020, PD No. 1445, and other pertinent rules and regulations in the payment of COVID-19 Hazard Pay; and

require the refund of claims of COVID-19 Hazard Pay which are questionable in nature and in excess of PS Cap limitation.

We recommended the Management to instruct the:

Municipal Accountant: i) stop the practice of recording back as         Receivables-Disallowance those that have been previously settled to avoid inconsistencies between Accounting books and SASDC balances; and ii) ensure that all receivables-disallowance reported in the books are valid and shall be settled by payment of the amount disallowed; 

Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to (i) take the necessary actions to expedite the collection of the unsettled disallowances; (ii) exhaust all possible remedies to collect from each of the liable persons;

subsequently, cause all the certifying and approving officers, who took part in the disbursement of disallowed expenditures, to assume responsibility in the final settlement of the remaining balance of the disallowance; and

ensure that before allowing settlement of disallowances through installment payment the same was authorized and approved by COA.

