Municipal Engineering Office to determine the actual status of the aforementioned projects which were reported as complete and issue the  corresponding certificate of completion;

Municipal Accountant (i) to effect necessary adjustment in the books for projects reported as complete in order to reflect the correct balances of the CIP accounts (ii) prepare the adjusting entries for completed projects transferred to the related/appropriate PPE account and (iii) to provide the corresponding depreciation for the aforementioned assets.

We recommended the Management to instruct the BAC to:

adhere to the requirement of RA No. 9184 that no bidding and award of design and build contract shall be made unless the required preliminary design and construction studies have been sufficiently carried out;
conduct pre-procurement conference as prescribed under Section 20.2 of the RIRR of RA No. 9184 for infrastructure projects withABC of ₽5 million and above to ensure that the procurement is in accordance with the APP and ascertain the readiness of the procurement at hand; 

maximize the conduct of pre-bid conference to allow both the procuring entity and the prospective bidders to discuss, clarify and explain the eligibility requirement and the  technical and financial components of the contract to be bid;

require submission of the value engineering analysis of design and construction method; proof of ownership for all the equipment pledge to the project, the required Affidavits of Commitment to Work of key personnel and duly signed Construction Safety and Health Program of the contractor duly approved by the Department of Labor and Employment, the detailed program of work as required upon award; 

strengthen the internal control over eligibility checking, evaluation of bids and post-qualification of bidders to ensure completeness and veracity of the submitted documents; and

strictly abide by the standards set forth in RA No. 9184 and its Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations on all procurement activities of the Municipality.

We recommend the following courses of action:

Local School Board to strictly comply with the provisions of Section 272 of RA No.7160 and DBM-DepEd-DILG Joint Circular No. 1 dated January 19, 2017 in the prioritization of programs, activities and projects that should be included in the LSB Budget and ensure full implementation and utilization of all identified priority projects funded under SEF;

refrain from allowing the SEF fund to be utilized for expenses not authorized in the aforementioned law and regulations;

require the Local School Board to justify charging of Awards and Rewards under SEF.

We recommend the Management to:

require strict enforcement/ implementation of Municipal Ordinance No. 06-82 dated December 11, 2006 specifically on segregation of wastes; intensify the campaign on “no segregation, no collection” policy; and firmly impose fines and penalties against violators of prohibited acts to ensure compliance of all and to provide additional funding for solid waste management activities;

ensure active participation of  all households, commercial businesses / establishments, institutions and market vendors in segregation and proper waste disposal at source;

take appropriate action necessary for the improvement of the existing Material Recovery Facility (MRF) of the Municipality to make it operational; 

prioritize the implementation of programs and projects identified in the Solid Waste Management Plan and Annual Investment Plan pertaining to solid waste management; and

consider the creation of plantilla position of Municipal Environmental Officer (MENRO) who will handle the implementation of solid waste management programs, projects and activities.

We recommend the Management:

issue demand letters to the accountable officials, employees and taxpayers with outstanding receivables particularly those of more than ten years, and exhaust all means to collect dormant receivable accounts;

strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated   December 19, 2016 and COA Circular No. 2012-004 dated November 28, 2012 on the required analysis of dormant accounts by performing the regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of the existence of the receivables for strict monitoring and disposition of said accounts; and for possible request for the write off of the specified dormant receivables to the Commission on Audit;

provide for allowance for impairment for dormant receivables in order to have a fair presentation of the financial statements as required under PPSAS 29. Compute/determine impairment in accordance with the Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards or Philippine Financial Reporting Standards.

We recommend the Local Chief Executive to:

direct the Municipal Engineer to require the concerned contractor to complete and rectify the unfinished projects and those that did not conform with the approved plans and specifications as soon as possible and impose appropriate sanctions and penalties, if warranted;

intensify the monitoring of all on-going projects to minimize defects and avoid acceptance of unfinished and defective projects and ensure proper review of contractor’s accomplishment of all implemented infrastructure projects prior to acceptance and full payment;  

require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to submit written justification on the full payment of infrastructure projects which are uncompleted and the Municipal Engineer for reporting as 100% complete despite being unfinished and reason/s why it should not be disallowed in audit; and

consider blacklisting DQT Builders from participating in subsequent procurement.

We reiterated our recommendation that the:

Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) undertake a thorough review of the bid documents submitted and strictly comply with post-qualification requirements mandated by Section 34 of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 relative to the procurement of government infrastructure project;

Technical Working Group (TWG) scrutinize the contractor’s manpower complement on all the projects to be awarded and not on an individual project only in cases where the latter is the lowest bidder in several projects which have the same or overlapping implementation period. This is in order to require the contractor to augment its manpower to be utilized in the project awarded to it or to disqualify it from obtaining several award or contract;

Technical Working Group justify for considering the Contractor as “passed” when in fact it had already pledged the same manpower complement to other agencies where the period of work overlapped with other projects; and

Contractor (i) strictly comply with the general description of the work embodied in the Contract; and (ii) submit Key Personnel’s Certificate of Employment to form part of the contractor’s bidding documents.

We reiterate our recommendation that the:

Market Supervisor in coordination with the Market Committee strictly follow/ implement  the zoning and sectioning  of the market stalls in accordance with the Municipal Ordinance; 

Market Committee conduct credit investigation of i) sub-lease occupants and determine their capacity to sustain payment of fees and charges, otherwise disqualify them; and ii) would be applicants to ensure compliance with the Municipal Ordinance; 

Market Supervisor and the Municipal Treasurer to enforce the penalties for violation of the prohibitory provisions embodied  in Section 51 of Municipal Ordinance No. 180 series of 2015; and


Market Supervisor conduct regular monitoring of the establishments inside the New Market to prevent market activities not compliant with the Ordinance.

We recommend the Management to:

maximize the utilization of the 20% Development Fund and ensure implementation and completion of the priority programs and projects identified for the benefits of its constituents;

adhere strictly to the guidelines provided under DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 to ensure efficient output, come up with projects with developmental impact that would improve more the  socio-economic conditions of the greater number of its constituents.

We recommend the Local Chief Executive to:

stop the practice of undertaking trainings and seminars or similar activities in place outside the official stations or territorial jurisdiction funded out of public funds;

identify what seminars/ trainings are to be considered as vital to the municipal government’s operation in the same manner that only the legitimate and specific target participants, who can reecho the various topics and pointers discussed in these activities to the colleagues, will be authorized to go on official travel;

strictly adhere with the provisions of Section 4 of RA No 6713 and                                 DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2011-59 as it enjoins the local officers and employees to be prudent in the use of the scarce resources of the government; and

stop incurrence of the same expenditures on CY 2018 onwards which are deemed excessive expenditures and are disallowable in audit.

We recommend the Management to:

instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the corresponding Journal Entry Voucher and effect necessary adjustment to record the audit disallowances totaling ₱7,524,552.75 which become final and executory. Moreover, ensure reconciliation of the recorded balances with RADC and SASDC issued by this Office;

require the Municipal Accountant to submit justification for failure to  record the aforementioned disallowances which became final and executory; 

strictly adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No.2009-006 dated September 15, 2009 on Settlement of Accounts; and

require the liable persons to comply with the NFD and COE to ensure settlement of disallowance within the prescribed period.

We recommended the management to:

Instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and the Municipal Engineer, being the concerned officials, to undertake the safe closure of the dumpsite at Lupac, Boac, Marinduque to ensure a healthy and conducive environment in the riverside area;

See to it that the waste segregation scheme, being mandatory as provided under RA 9003, will be implemented through close coordination with the component barangays, especially in the Poblacion area for a more effective solid waste management program;

Ensure that materials recovery facility is operational and utilized inasmuch as the Municipal Engineer reported it to be substantially complete; and

Undertake steps in the end that the municipality will be fully compliant with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9003 for a more comprehensive solid waste management program to maintain a pollution-free municipality.

We recommended various courses of action, as follows:

Instruct the heads of the municipality’s economic enterprises to review their respective plans and targets for a more effective direction of their operation;

Conduct consultations/seek public audience with various sectors of the community to determine their comments and impressions in view of the operation of the public market, slaughterhouse, waterworks and the health and diagnostic center;

Formulate measures on how to run these enterprises more effectively and efficiently through an enhanced monitoring and management systems; and

Review the financial attributes of the subject enterprises to optimize various aspects as to logistics and personnel to avoid incurrence of net losses in their operation.
